AGI -&nbsp;The illegal detention of fentanyl, in the United States, has undergone an increase of more than 1.700% between 2017 and 2023. In addition, in the same period, the share of total fentanyl seizures concerning the pills is quadrupled, with 115.6 million pills seized in 2023 representing 49% of total seizures. It reveals an analysis led by scientists from NYU Grossman School of Medicine and the University of Florida, published in the International Journal of Drug Policy.
&nbsp;
"It's the first time data published so updated about seizures that distinguish between fentanil powder and pills," the researchers explained. Drug seizures by law enforcement agencies are used as an indicator of availability or drug supply, but do not necessarily indicate the prevalence of illicit drug use. Fentanil is a synthetic opiate analgesic up to 50 times more powerful than heroin and involved in about two-thirds of all U.S. overdose cases. More than 100,000 people continue to die for fentanil abuse every year. Research also reveals that fentanil seizures vary from region to region in the United States. Initially, fentanil seizures were less common in the western part; However, by 2023, the western area had the largest number of seizures in terms of weight and 85% of all fentanil pills confiscated. The largest number of fentanil seizure powder, which can be easily used to adulter other drugs and make them more lethal, was recorded in the South. While the Midwest showed a lower number of fentanil seizures overall, a particularly high peak was noted in the seizure of fentanil.&nbsp pills;
&nbsp;
"Circa half of the seized fentanil is now in the form of pills, which suggests that the panorama of illicit drugs has changed rapidly," said Joseph J. Palamar, associate professor at the Department of Health of the NYU Langone Health and deputy director of the National Drug Early Warning System.
"Fentanil in the form of pills not only facilitates the beginning of use, but also increases the possibilities that people who purchase illicit pills can be unintentionally exposed to fentanil, as it is commonly present in pressed counterfeit pills to resemble oxycodone, Xanax or even Adderall", Palamar continued, who is also the main author of the study.
&nbsp;
Scientists have analyzed the annual trends of the seizure of pills and powders containing fentanil using the data of the program 'High Intensity Drug Trafficking Areas', or HIDTA, in the United States, from 2017 to 2023. Unlike most survey data and surveillance systems, which can delay a year or more, HIDTA data is available quarterly, allowing almost real-time analysis. The research team measured eight indicators of potential changes in the offer or availability of illicit fentanil, including the number of total seizures, dust seizures, pill seizures and the total weight of seizures. In addition, scientists examined the percentage of seizure of pills compared to the total of seizures. In the United States, between 2017 and 2023, 66,303 seizures were carried out, with 67.3% of fentanil seizures powder and 32.7% in pills. The total number of seizures in this period has increased by more than 1.700%.
&nbsp;
In 2023, states with the largest number of seizures were Florida, Arizona and California respectively. The largest number of pills were found in Arizona, Colorado and New Mexico. The Northeast, however, had the least number of pills seized in 2023. "The West reported the largest percentage of fentanil pills compared to all seizures, most likely due to the proximity to the Mexican border," said Palamar.
&nbsp;
The results of the study show that all regions are slowly recovering ground and that the pills are dominating much of the fentanil market. States with the highest percentage of seizures in pills are New Mexico, with 98.4%, Colorado, with 94.8% and Wyoming, with 93.8%. A limitation of the study identified by Palamar is that, due to the nature of HIDTA data collection, scientists have not been able to distinguish whether the seizures concerned exclusively fentanil, phentanil combined with other drugs or phentanil analogues, such as carfentanil, one of the most powerful opioids existing. However, according to Palamar the detection of fentanil in a drug seizure may be an important indicator of the risk of overdose.&nbsp;

