AGI -&nbsp; Russian forces continue their advance > across north-eastern Ukraine, conquering a series of small settlements along the border and forcing Ukrainian troops to withdraw from some positions. This, according to both Russian and Ukrainian military sources, the situation at the front in the conflict between Moscow and Kiev. The Russian Ministry of Defense has announced that its troops have occupied four other villages > (Gatische, Krasnoye, Morokhovets and Oleinkovo) located north of Kharkiv, > the second largest city in Ukraine, following the new offensive launched last Friday. The same Ukrainian armed forces admit that the Russian army is strongly advancing from the Russian-Ukrainian border to Kharkiv.
&nbsp;
"Today, during heavy fighting, our defenders were forced to withdraw from some other positions and another settlement passed completely under Russian control," said Hostri Kartuzy, a member of Ukrainian special forces. The leaders of Kiev decided to replace the commander> of the Ukrainian forces of Kharkiv>. "According to the decision of the military leadership, from 11 May the brigade general Mykhailo Drapatoy was appointed commander of the tactical operating group of the troops 'Kharkiv', we read in the note cited by the news site. Drapaty, who replaces General Yuriy Galushkin>, also remains in the position of Deputy Chief of Staff of the Ukrainian armed forces. The new head of the Kharkiv front, until January of this year was head of the operating group "Kherson". He is known as one of the commanders who led the liberation of the right bank of the Kherson region in 2022. In February he was appointed Deputy Chief of Staff for Military Training.
&nbsp;
According to General Oleksandr Syrsky, military commander of the Ukrainian army, the situation in the Kharkiv region is "meaningly worsened" last week, although Russian attempts to break down Ukrainian defensive lines so far have not been successful. The Ukrainian troops, in numerical inferiority and without weapons, are already at the limit in an attempt to defend a front of 600 miles from the south of Kharkiv to the city of Kherson on the Black Sea. With the opening of a new northern front of Kharkiv, the Russian army aims to further stretch the Ukrainian lines and make it easier to break into some points, say the military experts cited by the New York Times.
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
"The Russians have understood, just as many analysts, that the main disadvantage currently suffering Ukraine is men," said Franz-Stefan Gady, a military analyst living in Vienna. "Using the first line, increase the likelihood of a turn." Gady and other experts said that the immediate goal of the new Russian offensive is to force the Ukrainian army to withdraw troops south of Kharkiv, especially around the merlate city of Chasiv Yar, a Ukrainian strategic stronghold in the south-east of the region of Donetsk.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
<h2 Police chief, Vovchansk is becoming the new Bakhmut</h2>
The city of Vovchansk in the Kharkiv > region is "transforming" in Bakhmut or Maryinka > due to the continuous air attacks of the Russians.>&nbsp; The Chief Police of the Kharkiv region, Volodymyr Tymoshko, as RBC-Ukraine reports. In the three days since the beginning of the Russian offensive, Vovchansk "has suffered as it did not suffer since 2022", said Tymoshko: in particular, the Russians use a large number of air bombs guided to attack the city. "This is a 250-inch bomb or even 500 kilograms, which can demolish a multi-storey building. In a way, Vovchansk is turning into Bakhmut or Maryinka," he said. Tymoshko says the enemy's goal is not only the Ukrainian army, but also the police and rescuers. Therefore, armored vehicles are involved in the evacuation of civilians. According to the police chief of the Kharkiv region, the Russians use the tactics of the burned land, when a certain territory is bombarded with artillery and anti-aircraft guns before the entrance of the troops.&nbsp;
<h2> Belgorod
It is 15 dead the definitive balance of the victims of the collapse of a residential building in the Russian city of Belgorod. The Tass agency reports it. The city and its suburbs - reports the press organ - "have been subject to massive bombing by the Ukrainian armed forces on May 12. Fragments of a damaged Tochka-U tactical missile damaged a 10-story residential building, causing one of its sections to collapse." &nbsp;

