AGI -&nbsp;&nbsp; South Korea will set up a package of aid worth over $7 billion to support its semiconductor industry. This initiative follows the commitment assumed last year to build the world's largest chip center using $240 billion private investment, mainly by Samsung Electronics, the world's largest memory chip manufacturer. The government "is preparing a support package of over $7.2 billion to support the 'fabless', chip materials and production equipment in all sectors of the chip industry", said the Finance Minister, Choi Sang-mok. The $7.2 billion package could be created through "a new fund funded by public and private financial institutions", said Choi to managers of national chip manufacturers.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
&nbsp; The initiative arrives while the fourth Asian economy aims to invest heavily in six key technologies, including chips, displays and batteries, all areas where the country's technological giants are already well established. South Korea hosts two of the world's largest memory chip manufacturers: Samsung Electronics and SK Hynix. The semiconductors are the main export of Seoul and in March they reached 11.7 billion dollars, the highest level in almost two years, representing a fifth of the total exports of South Korea, according to the data disseminated by the Ministry of Commerce.
In May 2022, Samsung announced a massive investment plan of 450.000 billion won for the next five years, with the aim of becoming a leader in key sectors, from semiconductors to organic products. Ensure advanced chip supplies has become a crucial issue internationally, with the United States and China engaged in a fierce battle for chip market control.

